{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17486970","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17486970"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:52:01+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:52:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"220"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"220","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/220"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.18,0.33,0.03,0.44]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"220"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"91931"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"220","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/220"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"220"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75397"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"3465"},{"type":"tags","id":"3467"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"9124"},{"type":"tags","id":"9127"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12921"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11187"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31117"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"91931","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/91931"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old man is admitted to hospital with a 24-hour history of increasing lower abdominal pain. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He is a non-smoker and drinks two standard alcoholic drinks a day. On examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 100/min, blood pressure 110/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 96% on room air, and temperature 37.8\u00b0C. Abdominal examination reveals diffuse abdominal tenderness with guarding in the left iliac fossa. A CT scan shows extensive sigmoid diverticulae, a 5 cm pericolic abscess, mesenteric stranding, free fluid in the pelvis and a pneumoperitoneum.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate plan of definitive management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Colonic endosponge","Percutaneous drainage","Laparoscopy and lavage","Intravenous antibiotics","Sigmoid colectomy and end colostomy"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has had an episode of diverticulitis which has been complicated by the development of a pericolic abscess and free perforation. This is a relatively large abscess (5 cm) and there is clinical evidence (guarding) and radiological evidence (pneumoperitoneum, free fluid) of perforation with the inflammatory process spreading to the surrounding tissues. The most appropriate plan of management is a laparotomy, peritoneal washout, \u003Cstrong\u003Esigmoid colectomy and end colostomy\u003C/strong\u003E. This is classified as Hinchey stage III/IV diverticulitis (perforated diverticulitis with purulent or fecal peritonitis), which requires urgent surgical intervention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPercutaneous drainage\u003C/strong\u003E may be appropriate for isolated diverticular abscesses (Hinchey stage II) without evidence of free perforation or peritonitis. While this is less invasive, it would be insufficient in this case given the presence of pneumoperitoneum indicating free perforation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELaparoscopy and lavage\u003C/strong\u003E has been investigated as a less invasive alternative for perforated diverticulitis, but recent trials  have shown mixed results. It may have a role in selected cases with limited contamination, but given this patient\u0027s clinical presentation with evidence of diffuse peritonitis, resection is preferred.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous antibiotics\u003C/strong\u003E alone would be inadequate treatment for perforated diverticulitis with peritonitis. While antibiotics are an important component of treatment, they must be combined with source control through surgical intervention in this scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EColonic endosponge\u003C/strong\u003E (endoscopic vacuum-assisted closure) is primarily used for the management of anastomotic leaks after colorectal surgery or for chronic presacral sinuses. It is not indicated for the acute management of perforated diverticulitis with peritonitis, which requires urgent surgical intervention to control contamination.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Perforated diverticulitis with peritonitis and a large pericolic abscess requires urgent surgical intervention with sigmoid colectomy and end colostomy.","Conservative management with antibiotics alone is insufficient for perforated diverticulitis with peritonitis.","Percutaneous drainage may be appropriate for isolated abscesses without peritonitis or perforation."],"references":["Tochigi T, Kosugi C, Shuto K, Mori M, Hirano A, Koda K. Management of complicated diverticulitis of the colon. Ann Gastroenterol Surg. 2017;2(1):22-27. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29863123/#:~:text=Operative%20treatment%20is%20considered%20standard,case%2Dby%2Dcase%20basis.","Sartelli M, Weber D, Kluger Y, et al. 2020 update of the WSES guidelines for the management of acute colonic diverticulitis in the emergency setting. World J Emerg Surg. 202;15. Available at: https://wjes.biomedcentral.com/articles/10.1186/s13017-020-00313-4#Sec12"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75397"}},"question":{"data